HOME BACKUP MANIFEST
Version: 1.0
Method: Git
Scope: User home directory (curated)

PURPOSE

Maintain a portable, versioned backup of user configuration and essential
user data across multiple Arch Linux environments, including desktop and
mobile chroot systems. The backup must function offline and synchronize
when connectivity is available.

BACKUP MODEL

The backup is selective. Only files explicitly tracked by Git are included.
The backup is authoritative for configuration, not bulk data.

Git is used as:
- change tracker
- transport mechanism
- conflict resolution system

Git is not used as:
- full filesystem snapshot
- binary archive
- permission or ACL store

INCLUDED DATA

Eligible data classes:
- shell configuration files
- editor configuration files
- application configuration under .config/
- user scripts and binaries
- documentation and text files

Examples:
- ~/.zshrc
- ~/.bashrc
- ~/.profile
- ~/.config/
- ~/.local/bin/
- ~/scripts/
- ~/notes/

EXCLUDED DATA

The following must never be tracked:
- caches
- temporary files
- downloads
- media collections
- browser profiles
- large binary files
- auto-generated state

Examples:
- ~/.cache/
- ~/.local/share/Trash/
- ~/Downloads/
- ~/Videos/
- ~/Music/
- node_modules/
- build artifacts

PERMISSIONS

Git preserves:
- file contents
- directory structure
- executable bit
- symbolic links

Git does not preserve:
- ownership
- ACLs
- extended attributes

Files requiring such metadata are out of scope.

REPOSITORY LAYOUT

Supported layouts:
1. Dedicated repository directory with symlinks into $HOME
2. Bare repository using $HOME as the work tree

In all cases:
- repository metadata must not pollute the working tree
- untracked files remain hidden by default

SYNC POLICY

- Commits may be created offline
- Synchronization is via push and pull
- Conflicts are resolved manually
- History is never rewritten

The last successful pull defines the local baseline.

SECURITY

- Access is authenticated
- Transport is via SSH or physical media
- Secrets are excluded or encrypted before commit

Plaintext credentials are never tracked.

FAILURE MODES

- Repository loss does not imply total data loss
- Loss of untracked data is acceptable
- Corruption is mitigated by multiple clones

NON-GOALS

- Full system backup
- Disaster recovery for / or /var
- Permission or ACL replication
- Automated merge resolution

END OF MANIFEST

